# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bilimbi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] The fruit is ellipsoidal, elongated, measuring about 4 – 10 cm and sometimes faintly 5-angled.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] The skin is smooth to slightly bumpy, thin, and waxy turning from light green to yellowish-green when ripe.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] The flesh is crisp and the juice is sour and extremely acidic and therefore not typically consumed as fresh fruit by itself.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] The odd-pinnate leaves hang down at night, then raise in the morning in stages like "two steps forward, one step back" and descend in the same manner in the evening.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] Outside of Asia, the tree is cultivated in Zanzibar.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In 1793, the bilimbi was introduced to Jamaica from Timor and after several years, was cultivated throughout Central and South America where it is known as **mimbro**.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Suriname, this fruit is known as *lange birambi*.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] Introduced to Queensland at the end of the 19th century, it has been grown commercially in the region since that time.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Guyana, it is called Sourie, One Finger, Bilimbi, and Kamranga.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] This is a tropical tree, less resistant to cold than the carambola, growing best in rich and well-drained soil (but also stands limestone and sand).
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] It prefers evenly distributed rainfall throughout the year, but with a 2- to 3-month dry season.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] Therefore, the species is not found, for example, in the wettest part of Malaysia.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Florida, where it is occasionally cultivated as a curiosity, the tree needs protection from wind and cold.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Indonesia, *A. bilimbi,* locally known as *belimbing wuluh,* is often used to give a sour or acidic flavour to food, substituting tamarind or tomato.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In the northwestern province of Aceh, it is preserved by salting and sun-drying to make *asam sunti,* a kitchen seasoning to make a variety of Acehnese dishes.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] It is a key ingredient in many Indonesian dishes such as *sambal belimbing wuluh*.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In the Philippines, where it is commonly called *kamias* and *ibâ*, it is commonly found in backyards.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] The fruit are eaten either raw or dipped in rock salt.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] It can be either curried or added as a souring agent for common Filipino dishes such as *sinigang*, *pinangat* and *paksiw*.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] It can be sun-dried for preservation and used as a spice.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] It is also used to make a salad mixed with tomatoes, and chopped onions, with soy sauce as dressing.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] The uncooked bilimbi is prepared as relish and served with rice and beans in Costa Rica.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In the Far East, where the tree originated, it is sometimes added to curry.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Malaysia and the Philippines, bilimbi or kamias is made into a rather sweet and sour jam, with a flavour profile similar to prunes or plums.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Kerala and Coastal Karnataka, India, it is used for making pickles and fish curry, especially with sardines, while around Karnataka, Maharashtra, and Goa the fruit is commonly eaten raw with salt and spice.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Guyana and Mauritius, it is made into achars/pickles.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Maldives where it is known as *bilimagu*, it is pickled with aromatic spices and eaten with rice and local Garudhiya (fish soup).
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] It is also used in various Maldivian local dishes such as Boakibaa and Mashuni as a souring agent.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Seychelles, it is often used as an ingredient to give a tangy flavour to many Seychellois creole dishes, especially fish dishes.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] It is often used in grilled fish and also (almost always) in a shark meat dish, called *satini reken*.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] It is also cooked down with onion, tomato, and chili peppers to make a sauce.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] Sometimes they are cured with salt to be used when they are out of season.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] Bilimbi juice (with a pH of about 4.47) is made into a cooling beverage.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] Additionally, the fruit can be preserved by pickling, which reduces its acidity.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] The fruit contains high levels of oxalate.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] Acute kidney injury due to tubular necrosis caused by oxalate has been recorded in several people who drank the concentrated juice on continuous days as treatment for high cholesterol.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] The fruit also contains the neurotoxin caramboxin.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] The combination of both substances can also cause acute kidney injury when the fruit is consumed in excess, akin to the case with carambola.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] Even for those with prior normal renal function, this can result in neurotoxic as well as nephrotoxic effects.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In Malaysia, very acidic bilimbis are used to clean *kris* blades.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In the Philippines, it is often used in rural places as an alternative stain remover.
[src:bilimbi/averrhoa-bilimbi] In the region of Addu in Maldives, the flowers of the bilimbi plant were commonly used in the 20th century as a cloth dye.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] As the study of biology became increasingly specialized, specific codes were adopted for different types of organism.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] To an end-user who only deals with names of species, with some awareness that species are assignable to genera, families, and other taxa of higher ranks, it may not be noticeable that there is more than one code, but beyond this basic level these are rather different in the way they work.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Such a name is called a **binomial name** (which may be shortened to just "binomial"), a **binomen**, **binominal name,** or a **scientific name**; more informally it is also historically called a **Latin name**.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] In the zoological code, ICZN, the system is also called **binominal nomenclature** (using the suffix *-inal* instead of *-ial*), meaning "two-name naming system".
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The first part of the name – the *generic name* – identifies the genus to which the species belongs, whereas the second part – the **specific name** or **specific epithet** – distinguishes the species within the genus.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] For example, modern humans belong to the genus *Homo* and within this genus to the species *Homo sapiens*.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] *Tyrannosaurus rex* is likely the most widely known non-human binomial.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The *formal* introduction of this system of naming species is credited to Carl Linnaeus, effectively beginning with his work *Species Plantarum* in 1753.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] But as early as 1622, Gaspard Bauhin introduced in his book *Pinax theatri botanici* (English, *Illustrated exposition of plants*) containing many names of genera that were later adopted by Linnaeus.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The introduction of two-part names (binominal nomenclature) for species by Linnaeus was a welcome simplification because as our knowledge of biodiversity expanded, so did the length of the names, many of which had become unwieldy.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] With all naturalists worldwide adopting binominal nomenclature, there arose several schools of thought about the details.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] It became ever more apparent that a detailed body of rules was necessary to govern scientific names.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] From the mid-19th century onwards, there were several initiatives to arrive at worldwide-accepted sets of rules.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The starting point, that is the time from which these codes are in effect (usually retroactively), varies from group to group, and sometimes from rank to rank.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] In botany and mycology, the starting point is often 1 May 1753 (Linnaeus, *Species plantarum*).
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] In zoology, it is 1 January 1758 (Linnaeus, *Systema Naturae*, 10th Edition).
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] On the other hand, bacteriology started anew, making a clean sweep in 1980 (Skerman et al., "Approved Lists of Bacterial Names"), although maintaining the original authors and dates of publication.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] There are also differences in the way codes work.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] For example, the *ICN* (the code for algae, fungi and plants) forbids tautonyms, while the *ICZN* (the animal code) allows them.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] These codes differ in terminology, and there is a long-term project to "harmonize" this.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] For instance, the *ICN* uses "valid" in "valid publication of a name" (=the act of publishing a formal name), with "establishing a name" as the *ICZN* equivalent.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The *ICZN* uses "valid" in "valid name" (="correct name"), with "correct name" as the *ICN* equivalent.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Harmonization is making very limited progress.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] There are differences in respect of what kinds of types are used.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The bacteriological code prefers living type cultures, but allows other kinds.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] There has been ongoing debate regarding which kind of type is more useful in a case like cyanobacteria.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] A more radical approach was made in 1997 when the IUBS/IUMS International Committee on Bionomenclature (ICB) presented the long debated *Draft BioCode*, proposed to replace all existing *Codes* with a harmonization of them.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The originally planned implementation date for the BioCode draft was January 1, 2000, but agreement to replace the existing *Codes* was not reached.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] In 2011, a revised *BioCode* was proposed that, instead of replacing the existing *Codes*, would provide a unified context for them, referring to them when necessary.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Changes in the existing codes are slowly being made in the proposed directions.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] However, participants of the last serious discussion of the draft BioCode concluded that it would probably not be implemented in their lifetimes.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Many authors encountered problems in using the Linnean system in phylogenetic classification.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] In fact, early proponents of rank-based nomenclature, such as Alphonse de Candolle and the authors of the 1886 version of the American Ornithologists' Union code of nomenclature already envisioned that in the future, rank-based nomenclature would have to be abandoned.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Another *Code* that was developed since 1998 is the *PhyloCode*, which now regulates names defined under phylogenetic nomenclature instead of the traditional Linnaean nomenclature.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] This new approach requires using phylogenetic definitions that refer to "specifiers", analogous to "type" under rank-based nomenclature.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Such definitions delimit taxa under a given phylogeny, and this kind of nomenclature does not require use of absolute ranks.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The *Code* took effect in 2020, with the publication of Phylonyms, a monograph that includes a list of the first names established under that code.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Some protists, sometimes called **ambiregnal protists**, have been considered to be both protozoa and algae, or protozoa and fungi, and names for these have been published under either or both of the *ICZN* and the *ICN*.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The resulting double language throughout protist classification schemes resulted in confusion.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Slime molds, plasmodial forms and other "fungus-like" organisms claimed by both protozoologists and mycologists include mycetozoans, plasmodiophorids, acrasids, and labyrinthulomycetes.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Fungi claimed by both protozoologists and mycologists include chytrids, blastoclads, and the gut fungi.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Other problematic groups are the Cyanobacteria (ICNP/ICN), the Rozellida and Microsporidia (ICZN/ICN).
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The zoological code does not regulate names of taxa lower than subspecies or higher than superfamily.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] There are many attempts to introduce some order on the nomenclature of these taxa, including the PhyloCode, the Duplostensional Nomenclatural System, and circumscriptional nomenclature.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] The botanical code is applied primarily to the ranks of superfamily and below.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] There are some rules for names above the rank of superfamily, but the principle of priority does not apply to them, and the principle of typification is optional.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] These names may be either automatically typified names or be descriptive names.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] In some circumstances, a taxon has two possible names (e.g., Chrysophyceae Pascher, 1914, *nom. descrip.*; Hibberd, 1976, *nom. typificatum*).
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Descriptive names are problematic, once that, if a taxon is split, it is not obvious which new group takes the existing name.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] Meanwhile, with typified names, the existing name is taken by the new group that still bears the type of this name.
[src:bilimbi/biological-nomenclature] However, typified names present special problems for microorganisms.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] In biology, a **common name** is a name of a taxon or organism that is based on the normal language of everyday life.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] It is often contrasted with the scientific name for the same organism, which is often based in Latin.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Common names can be used frequently, but that is not always the case.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Creating an "official" list of common names can also be an attempt to standardize the use of common names, which can sometimes vary a great deal between one part of a country and another, as well as between one country and another country, even where the same language is spoken in both places.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] A common name intrinsically plays a part in a classification of objects, typically an incomplete and informal classification, in which some names are degenerate examples in that they are unique and lack reference to any other name, as is the case with say, *ginkgo*, *okapi*, and *ratel*.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The form of scientific names for organisms, called binomial nomenclature, is superficially similar to the noun-adjective form of vernacular names or common names which were used by non-modern cultures.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] A collective name such as *owl* was made more precise by the addition of an adjective such as *screech*.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Linnaeus himself published a flora of his homeland Sweden, *Flora Svecica* (1745), and in this, he recorded the Swedish common names, region by region, as well as the scientific names.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The Swedish common names were all binomials (e.g. plant no.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] 85 Ren-losta); the vernacular binomial system thus preceded his scientific binomial system.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The geographic range over which a particularly common name is used varies; some common names have a very local application, while others are virtually universal within a particular language.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Some such names even apply across ranges of languages; the word for *cat*, for instance, is easily recognizable in most Germanic and many Romance languages.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Many vernacular names, however, are restricted to a single country and colloquial names to local districts.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Some languages also have more than one common name for the same animal.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] For example, in Irish, there are many terms that are considered outdated but still well-known for their somewhat humorous and poetic descriptions of animals.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Common names are used in the writings of both professionals and laymen.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Many examples of such common names simply are attempts to translate the scientific name into English or some other vernacular.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Such translation may be confusing in itself, or confusingly inaccurate, for example, *gratiosus* does not mean "gracile" and *gracilis* does not mean "graceful".
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Various bodies and the authors of many technical and semi-technical books do not simply adapt existing common names for various organisms; they try to coin (and put into common use) comprehensive, useful, authoritative, and standardised lists of new names.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Other attempts to reconcile differences between widely separated regions, traditions, and languages, by arbitrarily imposing nomenclature, often reflect narrow perspectives and have unfortunate outcomes.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] For example, members of the genus *Burhinus* occur in Australia, Southern Africa, Eurasia, and South America.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] A recent trend in field manuals and bird lists is to use the name "thick-knee" for members of the genus.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] This, in spite of the fact that the majority of the species occur in non-English-speaking regions and have various common names, not always English.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] For example, "Dikkop" is the centuries-old South African vernacular name for their two local species: *Burhinus capensis* is the Cape dikkop (or "gewone dikkop", not to mention the presumably much older Zulu name "umBangaqhwa"); *Burhinus vermiculatus* is the "water dikkop".
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The thick joints in question are not even, in fact, the birds' knees, but the intertarsal joints—in lay terms the ankles.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Furthermore, not all species in the genus have "thick knees", so the thickness of the "knees" of some species is not of clearly descriptive significance.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The family Burhinidae has members that have various common names even in English, including "stone curlews", so the choice of the name "thick-knees" is not easy to defend but is a clear illustration of the hazards of the facile coinage of terminology.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] For collective nouns for various subjects, see a list of collective nouns (e.g. a flock of sheep, pack of wolves).
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Some organizations have created official lists of common names, or guidelines for creating common names, hoping to standardize the use of common names.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The AFNS has been an official Australian Standard since July 2007 and has existed in draft form (The Australian Fish Names List) since 2001.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Seafood Services Australia (SSA) serve as the Secretariat for the AFNC.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The Entomological Society of America maintains a database of official common names of insects, and proposals for new entries must be submitted and reviewed by a formal committee before being added to the listing.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Efforts to standardize English names for the amphibians and reptiles of North America (north of Mexico) began in the mid-1950s.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The dynamic nature of taxonomy necessitates periodical updates and changes in the nomenclature of both scientific and common names.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The Society for the Study of Amphibians and Reptiles (SSAR) published an updated list in 1978, largely following the previous established examples, and subsequently published eight revised editions ending in 2017.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] More recently the SSAR switched to an online version with a searchable database.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] Standardized names for the amphibians and reptiles of Mexico in Spanish and English were first published in 1994, with a revised and updated list published in 2008.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] A set of guidelines for the creation of English names for birds was published in *The Auk* in 1978.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] It gave rise to *Birds of the World: Recommended English Names* and its Spanish and French companions.
[src:bilimbi/common-name] The Academy of the Hebrew Language publish from time to time short dictionaries of common name in Hebrew for species that occur in Israel or surrounding countries e.g. for Reptilia in 1938, Osteichthyes in 2012, and Odonata in 2015.
